DML COMMANDS:
	1. INSERT
		
		It supports 3 types of syntaxes
		1. INSERT INTO table_name VALUES(....)
				- should specify values corresponding to each and every attribute without missing and in the same order
				Ex: INSERT INTO FULLNAME VALUES("Emily","Thomas")
		2. INSERT INTO table_name(attribute_names) VALUES(.....)
				-Can leave out some columns if not required (for NULL and DEFAULT columns)
				Ex: INSERT INTO FULLNAME (fname) VALUES ("Emily")
		3. INSERT INTO table_name(....) SELECT QUERY

		NOTE: 1.If the column is of type string/date time/character they need to be enclosed in single quotes (not double quotes)
			  2.Multiple rows can be inserted through a single INSERT statement only when it is used with SELECT statement
	
	2. SELECT
	
		SELECT column_names FROM table_name
		SELECT * FROM table_name (if all columns are required)
		SELECT column_names FROM table_name WHERE _condition
		
		Here the illustrative algorithm is for each tuple t in table_name add t to the result
		
		Alias:
			1. without AS keyword
				Ex: SELECT Id EmpId, Name FROM Employee
			2. with AS keyword
				Ex: SELECT Id AS "EmpId", Name FROM Employee
				NOTE: Here remember to use double quotes for alias , otherwise oracle database treates it as a string if it is inside single quotes
		
		DISTINCT:
		    SELECT DISTINCT Dept FROM Employee
			
			Distinct can also be used with NULL columns to remove duplicate NULL values.
			DISTINCT must be used immediately after SELECT. Any attempt to use it between columns will result in error.
			Ex: SELECT Dept, DISTINCT Manager FROM EMPLOYEE (It will result in error
			
		NOTE: 1.Equal to operator cannot be used to check for NULL VALUES
				Ex: SELECT ID, EName FROM Employee WHERE BONUS = NULL
					-Here no rows will be displayed in the result
				So, we use IS NULL operator to check NULL values in columns
				
			  2.IN NULL
                If NULL is used with IN clause then the condition behavior is similar to = NULL (not is NULL). So, no rows will be selected
				IN Clause will remove duplicates before executing the query (if any)
				Ex: IN ('ETA','ETA')
				
			  3.Spaces in CHAR type
				Leading spaces are not ignored for CHAR data type. If you use them you will not fetch any records.
				Trailing spaces are ignored for CHAR data type.
				Trailing spaces are not ignored for VARCHAR2 data type.
				Leading spaces are not ignored for VARCHAR2 data type.
				
			  4.LIKE 
				% (any number of characters)
				_ (one character)
				
				Ex:SELECT ID, ENAME FROM Employee WHERE ENAME LIKE 'E%'
				  
				
	IMPORTANT TOPIC:
		Execution order:  F J W G H W S D O L
		mnemonic :Friendly Jovial  Workers   Grow    Healthy  Wealthy Strawberries  Designed    On      Land
					FROM	JOIN	WHERE	GROUPBY	  HAVING   WINDOW	SELECT		DISTINCT  ORDERBY	LIMIT
			-SELECT must always be executed after the WHERE clause
				Ex: SELECT EName FROM Employee WHERE Id=1
					-Here the filtering needs to happen on an Id column which is not included in the SELECT clause. 
					Unless SELECT executes after WHERE this functionality cannot be supported.
			-DISTINCT removes duplicates based on all columns of the SELECT clause
			-Thus DISTINCT is dependent on SELECT clause and it's execution must happen after SELECT clause.
			-WINDOW is not always part of standard order (depends on DB)
			
	3. UPDATE
	
		SYNTAX: UPDATE table_name SET _attribute =new_value
				UPDATE table_name SET attribute1 =new_value, attribute2=new_value WHERE condition
				
		NOTE:1. The UPDATE statement fails if the same column is updated multiple times in the same statement.
				Ex: UPDATE Employee SET SALARY = 100, SALARY = 200 WHERE ID = 1
			 2. All columns in a table including the PRIMARY KEY can be updated using UPDATE statement.
				Ex: UPDATE Employee SET ID = 6 WHERE ID = 5
			 3. Foreign key can be updated, but:
					-New value must exist in parent table
					-Or constraint must allow it
	
		
	4. DELETE
	
		DELETE FROM table_name (deletes all records)
		DELETE FROM table_name WHERE condition
		TRUNCATE TABLE table_name
		
		NOTE: TRUNCATE statement can also be used to delete data from tables. 
			  TRUNCATE statement deletes all records from the table as it does not support WHERE clause. 
			  TRUNCATE statement is a faster option compared to DELETE when you have to delete all records from the table.
			  Any attempt to delete a record that violates the foreign key results in a failure.
			  
